# Execution state

Single source of truth for the currently active task. Overwritten as the task progresses; reset to idle when the task finishes — the prior snapshot is retained incidentally by git (the commit history), never curated into a separate archive directory.

PM reads this when curious about progress; PM never edits it. Agents read it as their first step and update it as their last step.

---

## Task

<one sentence — what the active task is, in plain language>

## Status

<one word: idle | planning | coding | reviewing | fixing | pr-prep | blocked | done>

## Done

- <one bullet per completed step, in chronological order>

## Remaining

- <one bullet per outstanding step>

## Touched files

<list of files modified in this task — used by coder to avoid blind edits and by reviewer to scope the verification>

## Next step

<one sentence describing the next concrete action — what the next agent run should do>

## Validation

<command(s) to run after the next step lands, or "pending" if not yet decided>

## Notes

(optional — short notes about decisions made, blockers hit, things to remember for the next session)

---

## How to use this file

- **Agent step 1** — read this file before doing anything else. If it says "done", do not start work without explicit PM instruction to start a new task.
- **Agent step last** — overwrite this file with the new state before stopping. Each Done item maps to one logical step that just finished; Remaining stays accurate; Next step points at the next concrete action.
- **Session restart** — re-read this file. It should be enough to continue without scrolling chat history.
- **Task complete** — reset this file to a new task or to "Status: idle". The finished snapshot is kept by git (the commit history), not copied into a separate archive directory.
